I disagree with the idea of &quot;free will&quot;. As a Determinist I would say certain events and conditions caused the moron to inflict pain upon himself. From my point of view individuals do not even choose pleasurable acts. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  For instance, my physical construction may predispose me to enjoy certain tactile sensations you would not enjoy. Further, &quot;desires&quot; to entertain those tactile sensations would only be noticed by me under certain conditions. Most of the time I do not want to eat a chocolate candy bar, but every time I pass them at the grocery store I find myself wanting one. Some individuals are predisposed such that they can't walk by a candy bar display without buying one. My disposition allows me to walk by. I do not choose to walk by, conditions are such that I can walk by without buying one. I think that &quot;free will&quot; is an illusion. Individuals want to believe they are ultimately in control of their present and futures, but they are not. Personally, I gain great comfort understanding that what happens tomorrow is out of my control.<br>
<br>
Given a glimpse of my view above you can see how I might think concerning topics such as &quot;Justice&quot;. You brought up the exploits involved in raising children (I have some experience with that)... one thing I have observed is that children, for the most part, haven't a fucking clue about what it is they are doing! :P They exemplify what I point at above. Their physical &quot;make up&quot; and environment push and pull them to behave certain ways. Punishment and rewards become tools by which we change their environment to elicit desired behaviors. Most of the time children behave a certain way which causes parents to behave a certain way and it just goes back and forth. I will not belabor this further. I think you get the gist of what I am saying.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> &quot;He sure did bro. And I knew my daughter was gonna get her ass busted when purposely threw her dinner on the floor(and she did too, 'cause I told her). There are other forms of discipline, for example: giving her looks of guilt, or ignoring her until she would have recognized that she hurt me by doing something that goes against my ideal for her(as I love her and don't want her to suffer) Certain scenarios require certain forms of mirrored truth. <br>
We are like children.&quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I think you are alluding to something other than property of omniscience which is attributed to the god of most western theologies. What I think you are pointing to is something more like an &quot;educated guess&quot; that can only come through experience. You might have an educated guess that a child will toss food onto the carpet when given opportunity, but you do not know that the child will, in fact, toss food. The child may never toss food onto the carpet, as far as you know. But the idea of omniscience is that god *knows* event X will occur at t1 before it actually does. Indeed, he knew that the killer of John F. Kennedy would gun down the president before the killer was even born. In a real sense, the killer of JFK had no choice at all but to kill, if god is omniscient! Which brings me to &quot;justice&quot;... it is not at all just to punish one for actions they could not prevent due to god's foreknowledge (omniscience). In the case of the story of Adam and Eve it would not be just to punish all future individuals based upon actions Adam and Eve couldn't help but do. God knows that they will eat the forbidden fruit prior to creating them, yet he creates them and the fruit by which they are tempted! (Makes one wonder if god has &quot;free will&quot;?) Again, this is not like popping out a kid guessing that you will have to punish a misbehavior one day (educated guess). Alledgedly, this is a being that creates knowing full well that he will banish them from his presence shortly there after. So why the fuck would I want to spend an eternity with such a monster should he actually exist? I can unequivocally say that if I had to face that monster I would beg for hell knowing that an eternity out of his presence would truly be bliss. Think about it. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p>Lurikeen Mali'Kyre<BR>
